%[text] ## Problem 2. Seperation of variables: start-up Poiseuille flow
%[text] ### Background
%[text] Poiseuille flow is the steady, pressure-driven viscous flow of a fluid through a confined geometry, such as a pipe or between parallel plates. In this type of flow, viscosity resists the motion, while the pressure gradient drives the fluid forward, producing a characteristic parabolic velocity profile.
imshow('Poiseuille flow_ChatGPT Image.png'); %[output:1dc8d699]
%[text] <u>Objective</u>
%[text] We are **building** a **transient viscous-flow solution** by splitting the motion into a steady Poiseuille-type solution plus a time-dependent correction. This develops an understanding of how momentum diffuses through the fluid over time until the flow relaxes to its final steady parabolic profile.
%%
%[text] ### Analysis
%[text] #### 1. Governing equation
%[text] 
%[text] The COMPLETE physics governing this flow, is a linear momentum PDE \[Refer to handwritten notes, pp. 98 - 99, for the complete derivation.\]. 
%[text] $\\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial t} = -\\frac{1}{\\rho}\\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial x} + \\nu \\frac{\\partial^2 u}{\\partial y^2} \\qquad (2)$
%[text] Physics represented by each term:
%[text] $\\underbrace{\\rho \\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial t}}\_{\\text{Transient inertia}} = \\underbrace{-\\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial x}}\_{\\text{Pressure driving force}} + \\underbrace{\\mu \\frac{\\partial^2 u}{\\partial y^2}}\_{\\text{Viscous diffusion}}$
%%
%[text] #### 2. Boundary conditions and initial condition
%[text] 
%[text] <u>Boundary conditions</u>
%[text] No-slip condition at the walls --
%[text] $u(-h,t)=0 \\qquad t\>0$
%[text] $u(h,t)=0 \\qquad t\>0$
%[text] 
%[text] <u>Initial condition</u>
%[text] The fluid is initially at rest --
%[text] $u(y,0)=0 \\qquad -h \\le y \\le h$
%%
%[text] ### 3. (Particular) Steady solution
%[text] 
%[text] The physics governing the steady flow \[Refer to handwritten notes, pp. 100 - 101, for the complete derivation.\].
%[text] $u\_s(y) = -\\frac{1}{2\\mu}\\frac{dp}{dx}\\left(h^2-y^2\\right)$
%[text] 
%[text] $\\underbrace{u\_s(y)}\_{\\text{Steady velocity profile}} = \\underbrace{-\\frac{1}{2\\mu}\\frac{dp} dx}}\_{\\text{Pressure-driven forcing scaled by viscous resistance}} \\underbrace{\\left(h^2-y^2\\right)}\_{\\text{Parabolic spatial distribution due to viscous diffusion}}$
%[text] 
%[text] Physics represented by each term:
%[text] $\\underbrace{u\_s(y)}\_{\\text{Steady velocity profile}}$=$\\underbrace{-\\frac{1}{2\\mu}\\frac{dp}{dx}}\_{\\text{Pressure-driven forcing scaled by viscous resistance}}$$\\underbrace{\\left(h^2-y^2\\right)}\_{\\text{Parabolic spatial distribution due to viscous diffusion}}$
%[text] 
%[text] The *physical balance* represented by the steady equation itself is \[see handwritten, p. 102\]:
%[text] $\\underbrace{-\\frac{dp}{dx}}\_{\\text{Pressure force}} = \\underbrace{\\mu \\frac{d^2u\_s}{dy^2}}\_{\\text{Viscous diffusion of momentum}}$
%[text] This last equation is especially important physically:
%[text] - The pressure gradient continuously drives the fluid downstream 
%[text] - Viscosity diffuses momentum toward the stationary walls 
%[text] - The competition between these two effects creates the parabolic Poiseuille profile. \
%%
%[text] ### 4. Transient solution
%[text] 
%[text] The transient solution represents the temporary evolution of the velocity field as the fluid adjusts from its initial condition toward the final steady Poiseuille profile. Physically, it captures the diffusion and decay of momentum disturbances due to viscous effects until the flow reaches steady state.
%[text] $u\_t(y,t) = \\sum\_{n=0}^{\\infty} C\_n \\cos(k\_n y) e^{-\\lambda\_n t}$
%[text] 
%[text] Physics represented by each term:
%[text] $\\underbrace{u\_t(y,t)}\_{\\text{Transient velocity response}} = \\sum\_{n=0}^{\\infty} \\underbrace{C\_n}\_{\\text{Strength of each transient mode}} \\underbrace{\\cos(k\_n y)}\_{\\text{Spatial eigenfunction satisfying the wall boundary conditions}} \\underbrace{e^{-\\lambda\_n t}}\_{\\text{Temporal viscous decay of each mode}}$
%[text] \[see handwritten, pp. 102 - 110.\]
%%
%[text] ### 5. Eigenvalues and eigenfunctions
%[text] 
%[text] Eigenvalues represent the **allowed spatial momentum modes** that can exist inside the channel while still satisfying the wall boundary conditions.
%[text] 
%[text] $\\lambda\_n = \\frac{(2n+1)\\pi}{2h} \\qquad n=0,1,2,\\ldots$
%[text] More physically:
%[text] - Each $\\lambda\_n$ corresponds to a particular “shape” of the transient velocity distribution across the channel height. 
%[text] - The walls constrain the fluid, so only certain spatial wave patterns are permissible — these are the eigenmodes. 
%[text] - Larger eigenvalues correspond to higher-frequency spatial variations (more oscillatory structure across the gap). 
%[text] - Since the transient terms decay like  \
%[text] $e^{-\\nu \\lambda\_n^2 t}$
%[text] larger eigenvalues decay much faster due to viscosity.
%[text] So physically: Eigenvalues determine the characteristic spatial scales and decay rates of momentum diffusion in the flow. 
%[text] $\\text{Eigenvalues determine the characteristic spatial scales and decay rates of momentum diffusion in the flow.} }$
%[text] Eigenvalues determine the characteristic spatial scales and decay rates of momentum diffusion in the flow.​
%[text] Another way to think about it:
%[text] - The pressure gradient tries to establish the steady parabolic profile instantly. 
%[text] - But viscosity can only diffuse momentum at a finite rate. 
%[text] - The transient solution decomposes that adjustment process into a spectrum of allowable viscous diffusion modes. 
%[text] - The eigenvalues tell you how “large” or “small” each mode is spatially, and therefore how quickly it disappears in time. \
%[text] #### Separation of Variables & Eigenmodes
%[text] Assuming: $u\_t(y,t)=Y(y)T(t)$
%[text] produces spatial eigenfunctions:
%[text] $Y\_n(y) = \\cos\\left( \\frac{(2n+1)\\pi y}{2h} \\right), \\qquad n=0,1,2,\\ldots$
%[text] with wave numbers:
%[text] $k\_n=\\frac{(2n+1)\\pi}{2h}$​
%[text] and temporal decay:
%[text] $T\_n(t) = \\exp\\left\[ -\\nu \\left( \\frac{(2n+1)\\pi}{2h} \\right)^2 t \\right\], \\qquad n=0,1,2,\\ldots$
%[text] **Physical Interpretation**
%[text] - Each eigenmode represents a transient momentum-diffusion structure. 
%[text] - Higher modes decay faster due to stronger curvature. 
%[text] - The lowest mode dominates long-time dynamics. \
%% HW5 Problem 2 Part 5 — Eigenfunctions and Temporal Decay
clear; clc; close all;

%% Parameters
h  = 1;      % half-channel height
nu = 1;      % kinematic viscosity
N  = 5;      % number of modes retained

%% Domains
y = linspace(-h, h, 600);
t = linspace(0, 3*h^2/nu, 600);

%% ============================================================
%% Spatial Eigenfunctions Y_n(y)
%% Velocity profile plotted horizontally
%% Channel width/domain plotted vertically
%% ============================================================

fig = figure('Color','w'); %[output:7b3eb072]
fig.Theme = "Light"; %[output:7b3eb072]

hold on; %[output:7b3eb072]

for n = 0:N-1

    % Wave number
    k_n = (2*n + 1)*pi/(2*h);

    % Eigenfunction
    Y_n = cos(k_n*y);

    % Plot aligned with channel geometry
    plot(Y_n, y/h, 'LineWidth', 1.8); %[output:7b3eb072]

end

xlabel('Eigenfunction Amplitude, Y_n(y)'); %[output:7b3eb072]
ylabel('y/h'); %[output:7b3eb072]
title('Spatial Eigenfunctions (Cosine Modes)'); %[output:7b3eb072]
legend("n = " + string(0:N-1), 'Location', 'best'); %[output:7b3eb072]

grid on; %[output:7b3eb072]
axis tight; %[output:7b3eb072]

% Draw channel walls
xline(0,'k:'); %[output:7b3eb072]
yline(-1,'k','LineWidth',1.2); %[output:7b3eb072]
yline(1,'k','LineWidth',1.2); %[output:7b3eb072]

%% ============================================================
%% Temporal Amplitude Functions T_n(t)
%% ============================================================

fig = figure('Color','w'); %[output:4973a973]
fig.Theme = "Light"; %[output:4973a973]

hold on; %[output:4973a973]

for n = 0:N-1

    % Wave number
    k_n = (2*n + 1)*pi/(2*h);

    % Temporal amplitude
    T_n = exp(-nu*k_n^2*t);

    plot(t/(h^2/nu), T_n, 'LineWidth', 1.8); %[output:4973a973]

end

xlabel('t / (h^2/\nu)'); %[output:4973a973]
ylabel('T_n(t)'); %[output:4973a973]
title('Temporal Amplitude Decay'); %[output:4973a973]

legend("n = " + string(0:N-1), 'Location', 'best'); %[output:4973a973]

grid on; %[output:4973a973]
axis tight; %[output:4973a973]
%%
%[text] ### 6. Complete velocity field
%[text] $u(y,t) = \\frac{G}{2\\mu}(h^2-y^2) - \\frac{16Gh^2}{\\mu\\pi^3} \\sum\_{n=0}^{\\infty} \\frac{(-1)^n}{(2n+1)^3} \\cos\\left( \\frac{(2n+1)\\pi y}{2h} \\right) \\exp\\left\[ -\\nu \\left( \\frac{(2n+1)\\pi}{2h} \\right)^2 t \\right\]$
%[text] \[Ref. Handwritten notes, pp. 116\]
%% HW5 Problem 2 — Startup Poiseuille Flow Field
% Velocity field:
% u(y,t) = steady parabolic profile + transient Fourier correction

clear; clc; close all;

%% Parameters
G  = 1;        % imposed pressure-gradient magnitude, -dp/dx = G
mu = 1;        % dynamic viscosity
rho = 1;       % density
nu = mu/rho;   % kinematic viscosity
h  = 1;        % half-channel height

N_modes = 50;  % number of Fourier modes retained

%% Spatial and temporal domain
Ny = 300;
Nt = 200;

y = linspace(-h, h, Ny);

% Characteristic diffusion time scale
t_diff = h^2/nu;

t = linspace(0, 3*t_diff, Nt);

[Y,T] = meshgrid(y,t);

%% Steady solution
u_s = (G/(2*mu))*(h^2 - Y.^2);

%% Transient solution
u_t = zeros(size(Y));

for n = 0:N_modes-1
    k_n = (2*n + 1)*pi/(2*h);

    C_n = -(16*G*h^2)/(mu*pi^3) * ((-1)^n)/(2*n + 1)^3;

    u_t = u_t + C_n*cos(k_n*Y).*exp(-nu*k_n^2*T);
end

%% Total velocity field
u = u_s + u_t;

%% Surface plot: u(y,t)
fig = figure('Color','w'); %[output:3e636ba2]
fig.Theme = "Light"; %[output:3e636ba2]

surf(Y,T,u,'EdgeColor','none'); %[output:3e636ba2]
xlabel('y'); %[output:3e636ba2]
ylabel('t'); %[output:3e636ba2]
zlabel('u(y,t)'); %[output:3e636ba2]
title('Startup Poiseuille Flow: u(y,t)'); %[output:3e636ba2]
colorbar; %[output:3e636ba2]
view(135,30); %[output:3e636ba2]
grid on; %[output:3e636ba2]

%% 2D profiles at selected times
fig = figure('Color','w'); %[output:0dea9b0a]
fig.Theme = "Light"; %[output:0dea9b0a]

times_to_plot = [0, 0.05, 0.1, 0.25, 0.5, 1, 2, 3]*t_diff;

hold on; %[output:0dea9b0a]
for i = 1:length(times_to_plot)
    [~,idx] = min(abs(t - times_to_plot(i)));
    plot(u(idx,:), y, 'LineWidth', 1.8); %[output:0dea9b0a]
end

xlabel('u(y,t)'); %[output:0dea9b0a]
ylabel('y'); %[output:0dea9b0a]
title('Velocity Profiles During Startup'); %[output:0dea9b0a]
% Create legend entry showing nondimensional time (t = characteristic length / diffusivity)
legend("t = " + string(times_to_plot/t_diff) + " h^2/\nu", ...
    'Location','best'); %[output:0dea9b0a]
grid on; %[output:0dea9b0a]
axis tight; %[output:0dea9b0a]

%% Centerline velocity versus time
u_center = interp2(Y,T,u,0*ones(size(t)),t);

fig = figure('Color','w'); %[output:6df60a2e]
fig.Theme = "Light"; %[output:6df60a2e]

plot(t/t_diff, u_center, 'LineWidth', 2); %[output:6df60a2e]
xlabel('t / (h^2/\nu)'); %[output:6df60a2e]
ylabel('u(0,t)'); %[output:6df60a2e]
title('Centerline Velocity vs Time'); %[output:6df60a2e]
grid on; %[output:6df60a2e] %[output:4b8e72ae]
